+# Queued topic — 2026-05-06 (Wednesday, governance slot)
+
+**Source (verified):** Ethan Mollick, "Management as AI superpower: Thriving in a world of agentic AI," One Useful Thing, January 27, 2026.
+URL: https://www.oneusefulthing.org/p/management-as-ai-superpower
+
+## Why this fits Wednesday governance
+
+Section 7.2 of DC CAP's framework holds staff accountable for the quality and accuracy of any AI-assisted work product. Section 7.3 requires staff authorship on all external communications. Mollick's argument supplies the empirical backing: the people who get useful work out of AI are the ones who can specify the goal, evaluate the output, and give feedback when it's wrong — the same management discipline DC CAP's framework expects. Frame this as the empirical case behind the framework's accountability rules.
+
+## Headline claims (all VERIFIED from the article)
+
+- Mollick taught a 4-day Wharton EMBA class where students built startup prototypes using Claude Code, Google Antigravity, ChatGPT, Claude, and Gemini. Output was an order of magnitude beyond what a full pre-AI semester used to produce.
+- Three variables drive the delegate-or-do-it-yourself decision: Human Baseline Time, Probability of Success, AI Process Time. ("Equation of Agentic Work.")
+- OpenAI's GDPval study: experts took ~7 hours per task; AI took minutes; expert checking took ~1 hour. GPT-5.2 Thinking and Pro models tied or beat human experts 72% of the time.
+- Three management moves raise probability of success and lower process time: clearer instructions, better evaluation/feedback, easier success-checking.
+- "If you can explain what you need, give effective feedback, and design ways of evaluating work, you are going to be able to work with agents."
+- "What's scarce is knowing what to ask for."
+- "The skills that are so often dismissed as 'soft' turned out to be the hard ones."
+- "The people who thrive will be the ones who know what good looks like — and can explain it clearly enough that even an AI can deliver it."
+
+## Pilot week alignment
+
+Tomorrow's run will detect Week 4 (Build Worth Keeping / Discernment) as `$ACTIVE_WEEK` unless the unhide flips overnight. The article maps cleanly to Week 4: a build that earns its keep is one whose creator can specify what good looks like and can evaluate when the AI got it wrong. The "five questions for delegation documentation" Mollick lists (what are we accomplishing, where are the limits of authority, what does done look like, what specific outputs, what interim outputs, what to check before finishing) overlap directly with the Week 4 Build Filter.
+
+If Week 5 unhides overnight, the article still works — Mollick's frame applies equally to iteration and inheritance.
+
+## Suggested title options
+
+- The Management Skills Are the AI Skills
+- Knowing What to Ask For Is the Scarce Resource
+- Mollick: The Soft Skills Turned Out to Be the Hard Ones
+- 7 Hours, 72%: When Delegating to AI Pays Off
+
+## Editorial framing notes
+
+- Open declaratively with the Wharton class outcome (4 days, MBA students, prototypes that beat semester-long pre-AI work).
+- Keep the math digestible: don't dump the equation; name the three variables and let the reader connect.
+- Tie the closing back to DC CAP's framework: 7.2 + 7.3 are management 101 dressed as a governance policy, and Mollick's evidence is why the framework was right to write it that way.
+- Editorial tag: any framing that pulls this article toward DC CAP's framework is Preston's synthesis, not Mollick's claim. Tag accordingly in sourceNotes.
+
+## Reminder for the agent that runs tomorrow
+
+After publishing, move this file to `daily_briefing/queued/_used/2026-05-06.md` so it does not trigger again.
